@Gromos≈Çaw ≈ömia≈Çy First: I know power plants are limited by physics, which is why I particularly focused on renewable energy. I don't really care much for fossil fuels, so even if coal plants miraculously upped their efficiency, I'd still likely be looking for renewable sources.
Second: traditional single-junction cells are just that. Traditional. They are what are reasonably affordable right now with respect to their efficiency (specifically silicon ones, which are in the 20s for efficiency).  It wouldn't surprise me if multi-junction cells became easier to manufacture over time, encouraging a price decrease. Multi-junction cells have a maximum theoretical efficiency easily over 40%. To play it safe, say we got multi-junction cells that operate at 30% efficiency. This is still around a 10% improvement over traditional cells (in their actual operation, not their theoretical limit), which I am sure would help deal with increased electrical demand. If, as I said, multi-junction cells become more reasonably priced in the future thanks to new production methods/techniques/mass production, then you see my point: an increase in efficiency would be nice. 
Obviously, everything has a theoretical limit. I'm just looking for the technology that has the greatest efficiency while still being practical.

