@Fhgffufufhffjg Well, first off emitting water isn't 0 emissions by definition. Second, your more powerful argument doesn't make sense either. Hydrogen Fuel Cell vehicles are electric cars. They still have a battery pack in them to store the electricity they produce, as the Fuel Cell generates a consistent amount of it. The nature of driving uses more or less electricity than a Fuel Cell produces at any given time. Example: Lets say a Fuel Cell produces 5kWh of electricity, if you are driving on level ground at a constant rate of speed my Fiat 500e uses about this much power to stay moving at 45mph. But, when I accelerate from a stand still I'm using upto 94kWh; but, at least 30 odd kWhs depending on how hard I accelerate. When coming to a stop I generate anywhere between 0kWh and 49kWh depending on my rate of velocity and the rate of deceleration. So, if I was generating 5kWh constant, I would be using more power generally than I was making.  So a Fuel Cell has to be large enough to produce and abundance of power over the average. Leading to waste. It may be only producing H2O; but, the efficiency is not there as in a Battery EV. It only uses what is uses and saves the rest for later. Now with the introduction of Ultra Capacitors the battery might be swapped or combined with in either one of these systems; but, the argument still applies, a Hydrogen Fuel Cell still needs to produce and excess of the average to keep power going. Then eventually you will run out and you will have to stop a fuel station and refuel. Might as well plug in when you get the chance.

Now finally, there is the Hydrogen infrastructure argument. How much energy are using to produce the Hydrogen? That energy has to come from somewhere. The infrastructure has to be installed in most places still. I'm not saying that EV chargers don't need to be installed; but, we can at least offset them with Solar PV or Vertical Wind Generators at the same time. So far, we are just missing the mark, we are not doing all that we can. Big Oil and Big Auto want you to think that Hydrogen Fuel Cell is the better solution. So you can buy their more complex systems, and their version of energy. Electric grids all around the world are getting "greener" all the time and they will only get better in the future.

Korea has a very well done Hydrogen Fuel Cell vehicle in the Hyundai Nexo if you are truly interested; but, my argument still remains.

