@Stephen Lord The warranty terms imply that testing has indicated an average pack life much longer than the warranty period/mileage, otherwise the carmakers wouldn't be offering those terms. The end of an EV packs life in transportation is generally given (in the warranty conditions) as a 30% loss of capacity.


However, if the car loses 30% capacity after 12-15 years it doesn't just stop working... it just has less range and is still useful for day-to-day driving. Though after this point capacity loss is often quicker, a good rough estimate is whatever time it took for the pack to reach 70% capacity is also roughly the time you'll have between 70% and dead. We're still talking terms of 15-25 years and mileages for modern packs in excess of 500,000km. We have around 3 million EVs on the road worldwide, some approaching or even exceeding the mileage of your diesel, almost all with telematics systems that report health metrics on the batteries (my own EVs telematics data are part of two university research programs) and in general the packs have held up under real world charging and driving far better than hoped.


And should you choose to replace a pack with 70% of it's capacity left... it still has a substantial resale value for grid storage.... even if it's completely dead there are lots of easily recoverable raw materials in the pack with a strong resale value. 100kg+ of aluminium, 40kg + of nickel etc for typical packs. One often used deceptive statistic is to apply the recycling rate for lithium ion batteries from small electronics to BEV batteries... when there is a difference in scale of 1000 fold or more in the quantities of recoverable materials... and that scale has an impact on the financial viability of recycling.

