@Adam King Correct:  There's more to environmental damage than mere pounds of carbon.  Exhaust and leakage components to the atmosphere (NOx, SOx, CO2, CH4...) are different between gasoline and coal.  Also, CO2 is just one of a host of different greenhouse gases.  (The video skipped the rationale for focusing only on the carbon emissions, but it's an informative, if incomplete perspective.)  The U.S. grid is approximately 30% coal-powered in 2018, so our iPhones, Teslas, and server farms are, also, fractionally coal-powered.  Crudely put, if they emitted the same amount of carbon, would you prefer a coal-powered car or a gas-powered car?  Coal's contribution AS A PERCENTAGE of the U.S. electric grid is, indeed, slowly falling over time, but since our demand for electricity is meanwhile zooming upward, our burning of coal is INCREASING.  We burn greater amounts of coal annually as time goes by, and that's mostly to drive the Tech Sector, including all its computers, networks, and phones.  (Surprise, coal fans.)

There was also no mention of one really huge factor making gasoline a desirable fuel: it has a very high energy-per-unit-mass value, especially in comparison to batteries, and gasoline is easily transportable at a tiny fraction of the cost of the energy it contains.  It's not a direct comparison, but electric transmission lines suffer significant losses simply due to heating up the wires as we try to send electric power to the end user.  As you point out, Adam, it's a whole new pile of data once we start to study the construction and operation of the fossil fuel infrastructure that brings our gasoline and try to compare that to the infrastructure detriments to the environment inherent in electric power generation, especially for coal mining.  Shall we consider health care costs, as well?  Lung cancer deaths-per-thousand-people, anybody?

My point:  The video is a sketch, a sort of back-of-the-envelope comparison between gas and electric cars, but the actual study of such things involves vastly more complexity than is presented here.  (Source: current Environmental Engineering student, Environmental Science degree, former nuclear reactor operator)

